               <head>Muhammad Shadiyabadi’s commentary on Khaqani’s poems</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of a work by Muḥammad ibn Dāʾūd ʿAlavī Shādiyābādī</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2006003807 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2002009961" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_1283x-item1">
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic </textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Substantial fragment from an apparently untitled commentary by Muḥammad ibn Dāʾūd ʿAlavī Shādiyābādī on the poetic compositions of a contemporary of Niẓāmī and poet at the court of the rulers of Shīrvān, Afz̤al al-Dīn Ibrāhīm ibn ʿAlī Najjār Shīrvānī, with the takhalluṣ Khāqānī (d. 595/1199). </p>
                        <p>The same author also wrote 1) a commentary on the qaṣāʾid or eulogies of the poet Anvarī, and 2) ʿAjāʾib al-ṣanāʾiʿ, a translation of the Kitāb fī maʿrifat al-ḥiyal al-handasiyyah of Ismāʿīl al-Jazarī, under the patronage of the Khiljī ruler of Mālvah, Sulṭān Nāṣir al-Dīn ibn Ghiyās̲ al-Dīn (d. 916/1510). </p>
                        <p>Defective at beginning, lacking preface or introduction. 
</p>
                        <p>The work is endorsed as Sharḥ-i qaṣāʾid-i Khāqānī, however, this is probably not the formal title. 
</p>
                        <p>Not dated at end. 
</p>
                        <p>Collation marks in margins. 
</p>
                        <p>Pencil foliation. 
</p>
                        <p>Rough nastaʿlīq by multiple hands. 
</p>
                        <p>Lacking original binding. </p>
                        <p>Miscellaneous boards: 1) cracked and delaminating board covered with combed marbled paper edged with brown leather; 2) delaminating tooled leather (internal textual and documentary matter exposed). 
</p>
                        <p>Paper dust wrapper (BEIC Home Department legal publication for the regulation of Registered Joint Stock Companies, March-June 1850); watermark (Britannia or Minerva in crowned oval frame, J Whatman Turkey Mill 1848); torn, creased, stains; labels. 
</p>
                        <p>Folios bound; cropped. 
</p>
                        <p>Condition fragile.
</p>
                     </note>
